~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Notes Specific to Apple's macOS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. include:: prologue.rst

.. contents::

Overview
========

This document describes platform-specific behaviour, build requirements,
and workarounds relevant when running BRLTTY on macOS.

Building from Source
====================

BRLTTY must be built from source on macOS.  Configure with
``--prefix=/usr/local`` so that the install targets do not attempt to write
to the read-only root filesystem (``/``):

.. code-block:: bash

   ./configure --prefix=/usr/local
   make -j4
   sudo make install

The build requires Xcode Command Line Tools (``xcode-select --install``) and
the following Homebrew packages:

* ``pkg-config`` â€” for locating library headers and flags
* ``liblouis`` â€” braille translation tables (optional but recommended)
* ``espeak-ng`` â€” speech synthesis (optional)

Running as Root
===============

BRLTTY needs root privileges to open USB and serial braille devices.
``brltty-term`` uses ``sudo`` to start BRLTTY.  Add the following entry to
``/etc/sudoers.d/brltty`` (adjust the username as needed)::

   username ALL=(root) NOPASSWD,SETENV: /usr/local/bin/brltty, /usr/local/bin/brltty-cleanup

The ``SETENV`` flag is required because ``brltty-term`` passes the user
environment to BRLTTY via ``sudo --preserve-env``.

BRLTTY Configuration
====================

A minimal ``/usr/local/etc/brltty.conf`` for a USB braille display::

   braille-driver NAME
   braille-device usb:
   api-parameters auth=none

Replace ``NAME`` with the two-letter driver code for your display
(e.g. ``fs`` for Freedom Scientific, ``ht`` for Handy Tech).

The ``api-parameters auth=none`` line disables BrlAPI key-file authentication.
The default key file is empty on a fresh macOS install, which causes the
server to reject connections; disabling authentication works around this.

The screen driver (``-xem``) is set on the command line by ``brltty-term``
and should not be set in ``brltty.conf``.

Sharing the Braille Display with VoiceOver
==========================================

VoiceOver and BRLTTY cannot share a USB braille display simultaneously.
When VoiceOver holds the device, BRLTTY cannot open it, and vice versa.

``brltty-handoff`` â€” described below â€” provides a mechanism to transfer
control of the display between the two.  Hammerspoon_ (a macOS automation
tool) can use ``brltty-handoff`` to perform the transfer automatically
whenever focus moves between the terminal emulator running brltty and any
other application.

brltty-handoff
--------------

``brltty-handoff`` is a small program that connects to the running BRLTTY
via BrlAPI and either suspends or resumes the braille driver:

``brltty-handoff suspend``
   Queries the active driver name, calls ``brlapi_suspendDriver()``, forks
   a background worker that holds the BrlAPI connection open (keeping the
   driver suspended), and writes the worker's PID to
   ``/tmp/brltty-handoff.pid``.  The parent returns immediately once the
   driver is confirmed suspended.

``brltty-handoff resume``
   Sends ``SIGUSR1`` to the background worker, which calls
   ``brlapi_resumeDriver()`` and exits.  If no worker is running (no PID
   file) the command is a no-op.

The background worker is necessary because the braille driver stays
suspended only while the BrlAPI connection remains open.  When the worker
receives ``SIGUSR1`` it resumes the driver and closes the connection so
BRLTTY can reclaim the device.

brltty-cleanup
--------------

``brltty-cleanup`` removes stale BrlAPI socket files from the BrlAPI socket
directory (``/usr/local/var/lib/BrlAPI`` by default).  Stale sockets
accumulate when BRLTTY exits uncleanly (crash, kill signal).  The cleanup
is a no-op when BRLTTY is already running.

``brltty-term`` calls ``brltty-cleanup`` automatically before starting
BRLTTY.

Hammerspoon Automation
----------------------

``Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua`` in the BRLTTY source tree is a
Hammerspoon_ configuration that watches for the terminal emulator running
brltty to gain or lose focus, and automatically hands off the braille
display between BRLTTY and VoiceOver.

The active terminal emulator is detected automatically by walking up
brltty's process ancestry (brltty â†’ sudo â†’ shell â†’ terminal app), so no
hardcoded application name is needed.  ``TERMINAL_BUNDLES`` near the top
of the file is a fallback allowlist used before brltty has started;
extend it if you use a terminal emulator not listed there.

**If Hammerspoon is not yet configured** on your machine, copy or symlink
``brltty.lua`` as your Hammerspoon entry point::

   cp Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua ~/.hammerspoon/init.lua
   # or: ln -s /usr/local/share/brltty/Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua ~/.hammerspoon/init.lua

**If you already have a** ``~/.hammerspoon/init.lua``, place ``brltty.lua``
in your Hammerspoon directory and load it from your existing config::

   cp Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua ~/.hammerspoon/brltty.lua

Then add the following line to your ``~/.hammerspoon/init.lua``::

   require("brltty")

Before the Hammerspoon config will work:

1. Install Hammerspoon: ``brew install --cask hammerspoon``
2. Grant Hammerspoon Accessibility permission in
   System Settings â†’ Privacy & Security â†’ Accessibility
3. In VoiceOver Utility â†’ General, enable
   "Allow VoiceOver to be controlled with AppleScript"

How the Handoff Works
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

When **the terminal emulator gains focus**:

1. Hammerspoon checks whether the focused app is the terminal running brltty.
   Before brltty has started, the ``TERMINAL_BUNDLES`` allowlist is used.
   Once brltty is detected running, its process ancestry is walked
   (brltty â†’ sudo â†’ shell â†’ terminal app) to identify the exact terminal and
   the result is cached for the rest of the session.
2. Hammerspoon polls every 0.5 s until BRLTTY is confirmed running.
3. VoiceOver is told to quit via AppleScript (clean shutdown, releases USB).
4. Hammerspoon waits until both VoiceOver and BrailleTranslationService
   have exited.
5. ``brltty-handoff resume`` is called so BRLTTY reclaims the display.

When **the terminal emulator loses focus**:

1. ``brltty-handoff suspend`` is called synchronously.
2. VoiceOver is started via VoiceOverStarter.

The ``HANDOFF_COOLDOWN`` (3 s) suppresses the spurious "away from terminal"
event that macOS fires when VoiceOver emits its startup announcement.

Spoken Announcements
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

While VoiceOver is off (during terminal use), macOS "Speak announcements"
(System Settings â†’ Accessibility â†’ Spoken Content â†’ Speak announcements)
is enabled automatically so that system notifications are still read aloud.
It is disabled again when VoiceOver resumes.  The original setting is
restored when Hammerspoon exits.

VoiceOver IOKit Device Release
===============================

On macOS, killing VoiceOver with ``SIGTERM`` or ``SIGKILL`` leaves the
IOKit USB user-client seize unreleased.  Any attempt to open the same USB
device (``USBDeviceOpenSeize``) fails with ``kIOReturnExclusiveAccess``
(``0xE00002C5``) for 60 seconds or more.

Using ``osascript -e 'tell application "VoiceOver" to quit'`` triggers
VoiceOver's normal AppleScript shutdown path, which releases the USB device
cleanly before exiting.

BrailleTranslationService
--------------------------

VoiceOver's braille support runs in a separate XPC process called
``BrailleTranslationService`` (inside ``ScreenReader.framework``).  After
VoiceOver quits, ``BrailleTranslationService`` continues to hold the USB
device for a few seconds.  BRLTTY must wait for this process to exit before
attempting to open the device.

The Hammerspoon config polls for both ``VoiceOver`` and
``BrailleTranslationService`` to be gone before calling
``brltty-handoff resume``.

VoiceOver Utility
-----------------

When VoiceOver Utility (the VoiceOver configuration app) is open, it keeps
``BrailleTranslationService`` alive indefinitely even after VoiceOver itself
has quit.  The USB device therefore remains held and BRLTTY can never reclaim
it.

The Hammerspoon config detects this and quits VoiceOver Utility automatically
as part of the handoff sequence, before quitting VoiceOver.  VoiceOver Utility
settings take effect immediately and have no unsaved state, so closing it
silently is safe.

Troubleshooting
===============

**Terminal shows blank on braille display**
   BRLTTY is using ``poll(2)`` instead of ``select(2)`` to monitor the PTY
   master.  On macOS ``poll(2)`` does not report activity on PTY or character
   devices; ``select(2)`` must be used instead.  Ensure the macOS fix in
   ``Programs/async_io.c`` is included in the build and reinstall BRLTTY.

**brltty-term prompts for a password**
   The sudoers entry is missing or lacks ``SETENV``.  Reinstall
   ``/etc/sudoers.d/brltty`` with the entry shown above.

**make install fails with "Read-only file system"**
   ``configure`` was run without ``--prefix=/usr/local``.  Re-run configure
   with the correct prefix, rebuild, and reinstall.

**Display not connecting after VoiceOver quits**
   Wait for ``BrailleTranslationService`` to exit (up to ~5 s).  The
   Hammerspoon config handles this automatically.

**BRLTTY fails with "another BrlAPI server is already listening"**
   A stale socket file exists from a previous crash.  ``brltty-cleanup``
   removes these automatically when called from ``brltty-term``.  Check
   that the sudoers entry permits running ``brltty-cleanup`` as root.

.. _Hammerspoon: https://www.hammerspoon.org/
